          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>A patient presents with partial drooping of the upper eyelid, but the eye can st</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>A patient presents with partial drooping of the upper eyelid, but the eye can still be partially opened. Which muscle's paralysis specifically accounts for the partial, rather than complete, nature of the ptosis?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Levator palpebrae superioris</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Paralysis of the levator causes complete ptosis, as it is the main elevator of the upper eyelid and is supplied by cranial nerve III.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Müller's muscle</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Müller's muscle is the smooth muscle component of the eyelid under sympathetic control. Its paralysis causes only partial ptosis because the striated levator palpebrae superioris remains functional.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Superior rectus</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The superior rectus elevates the eyeball, not the eyelid. Its paralysis impairs upward gaze, not lid elevation.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Orbicularis oculi</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The orbicularis oculi closes the eyelid. Its paralysis (facial nerve palsy) causes inability to close the eye, not ptosis.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The key distinction is between partial and complete ptosis. The levator palpebrae superioris (CN III) is the main lid elevator — its loss causes complete ptosis. Müller's muscle, under sympathetic control, provides only supplementary elevation, so its loss causes partial ptosis."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Correct! Müller's muscle provides supplementary eyelid elevation under sympathetic control. When sympathetic innervation is lost, as in Horner's syndrome, only partial ptosis results because the levator palpebrae superioris (CN III) continues to function."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
