          },
          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>A 55-year-old male smoker presents with right-sided ptosis, miosis, and anhidros</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>A 55-year-old male smoker presents with right-sided ptosis, miosis, and anhidrosis. Which neuron of the sympathetic pathway is most likely damaged?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>First neuron, due to a hypothalamic lesion</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>A hypothalamic lesion can cause first-neuron Horner's syndrome, but it is not specifically associated with a smoking history. The smoking history strongly points to the lung apex.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Second neuron, due to a Pancoast tumour at the lung apex</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The second preganglionic neuron loops over the lung apex, making it vulnerable to a Pancoast tumour — the classic cause in smokers. Anhidrosis confirms the lesion is proximal to the superior cervical ganglion.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Third neuron, due to internal carotid artery dissection</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Third-neuron lesions spare anhidrosis because sudomotor fibres to the face leave the sympathetic chain before the superior cervical ganglion. This patient has anhidrosis, ruling out a third-neuron lesion.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Ciliary ganglion, due to orbital inflammation</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The ciliary ganglion is a parasympathetic relay for pupil constriction and accommodation. It is not part of the sympathetic pathway that produces Horner's syndrome.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The combination of smoking history and anhidrosis is the key. The second neuron loops over the lung apex (vulnerable to Pancoast tumour), and anhidrosis appears only in first and second neuron lesions. Third-neuron lesions spare facial sweating."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Correct! The second neuron traverses the lung apex, where a Pancoast tumour in a smoker can damage it. Anhidrosis confirms the lesion is at or proximal to the superior cervical ganglion, distinguishing second-neuron from third-neuron Horner's syndrome."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
