          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>A patient presents with sudden complete ptosis, the eye deviated down and out, a</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>A patient presents with sudden complete ptosis, the eye deviated down and out, and a fixed dilated pupil. Which single finding most reliably identifies this as a surgical emergency requiring urgent imaging?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Complete ptosis</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Complete ptosis occurs in both surgical and medical oculomotor nerve palsy whenever the nerve fibres to the levator palpebrae superioris are affected. It does not distinguish the two.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Down and out deviation of the eye</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>This deviation occurs in any significant oculomotor nerve palsy because only the lateral rectus (CN VI) and superior oblique (CN IV) remain functional. It is not specific to surgical causes.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Fixed, dilated pupil</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Parasympathetic pupillomotor fibres travel on the surface of the oculomotor nerve and are compressed first by structural lesions such as a posterior communicating artery aneurysm. Ischaemic palsy from diabetes typically spares the pupil.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Diplopia in all gaze directions</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Diplopia is expected in any complete oculomotor nerve palsy regardless of cause. It cannot distinguish surgical from medical aetiology.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Remember the 'pupil-sparing rule.' In compressive (surgical) CN III palsy, the superficial parasympathetic fibres are compressed first, dilating the pupil. In ischaemic (medical) palsy, the pupil is usually spared. A new CN III palsy with a dilated pupil demands emergency imaging to exclude a posterior communicating artery aneurysm."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Correct! Pupil involvement is the critical differentiator. Parasympathetic fibres on the nerve surface are compressed early by aneurysms or tumours, dilating the pupil. Ischaemic damage from diabetes or hypertension affects the nerve core and typically spares the pupil."
                }
              ],
